data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + `ThreadAbortException`/`ResetAbort` as control flow.

### Why it breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it no longer terminates threads. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if the delegate itself doesn't check it.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ae.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls for this pattern

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | `Task.WaitAsync` abandons the *wait*, not the work. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop, it keeps running. Pass the `CancellationToken` into `work` and check it at regular intervals for true cooperative cancellation. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks an internal timer. Always `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from external cancellation. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` inside the work** | Won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. |

### For truly cooperative cancellation (recommended)

Change the signature to accept a token-aware delegate:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(token), token)
                   .WaitAsync(token)
                   .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then cooperate:

```csharp
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return "done";
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

This ensures work **actually stops** on timeout rather than being silently abandoned.
